rComments: The whole class had the potential to be awful (and he admitted that the textbook was pretty bad) but Dr Lundeen genuinely tried to make his class great. Lectures were super engaging, homework was fair, overalls great. The final was horrible BUT he ended up curving it, so aside from the added stress, he's a wonderful professor.

Professor Lundeen is an amazing person,homework questions,as well as the midterm were fair and solvable,HOWEVER, for the phy2311 final 2021 fall , which was "in-person" & "closed book",the questions were insanely difficult & much harder than previous year's "24 hour" and open book final,very unfair,even tho i learned, it'll still destroy my GPA.

rComments: It's hard to judge whether Lundeen's teaching style actually works or not. He insists we teach ourselves solely through a textbook he adamantly describes as being verbose and unclear. His expectations are wildly ambiguous and there's a massive disconnect between the homework he provides and the exam content. But at least the homework has bonuses.

The homework was generally fair but had a few tough questions, with opportunity for extra credit. This exam did not reflect the in class material in a fair way and felt harder than previous open book exams. P. Lundeen was a good lecturer and definitely cares for students but his expectations are not clear and make it hard to do well.

Really helpful and flexible prof. However assignment problems are condescendingly simple, as are the suggested textbook problems. In no way do they prepare you for the integrated problems expected on a final, and a very significant proportion of the class are expecting to receive failing grades on the final.

Considering the difficulty of the material at hand, Prof. Lundeen was awesome. He taught his course with the student in mind and was very understanding and compassionate. His lectures were immersive and were as good as any that I've had on zoom. I highly recommend him.
